metadata.name: Unfinished Loom #18
metadata.description:
The 'Unfinished Loom' is a generative system that produces variations of itself through rotations, displacements, and self-repetition. 

Self-similarity in the loom is achieved by repeating the double grid system and its elements vertically (using the 'o' and 'l' keys) and horizontally (using the 'i' and 'k' keys).

Pressing 'a' produces automatic changes, while pressing 'x' reverts to the original composition.

By clicking on the canvas, you can play with colors and transparency. 

The '1' key toggles between disorder and order. 
The '2' and '3' keys allow you to toggle displacements.
The '4' key enables you to switch between entropy or not.
The '5' key lets you switch between mixed textures or assigned textures. 

You can reduce, amplify, or flip the displacement using the 'u' or 'j' key. 
To remove a color press 'c'. To reset to all colors, press 'v'.

You can save a PNG file using 's', a JPG using 'd', a PNG with twice your window height using 'f', and a print size image using 'g'.

This work explores composition based on generative double grid system, where rotations, displacements and noisy lines intertwine to form a playful loom.

Created with p5.js rendering in WEBGL.

metadata.name: 二进蝌蚪 #49
metadata.description:
二进蝌蚪, which could loosely translate as "binary tadpoles", is the result of many constraints. 

The concept being explored here is the cognitive switch, that is to say the wildly different interpretations you can have of a same piece from the exact same point of view. How does your brain interpret, before any conscious processing, the data it is being fed? How do you project a representation of "life" on a static image?


In this case the switch is (not completely unexpectedly) binary. At one end, you see the tadpoles going about minding their own business. This view is strongly favoured by a lower tadpole density, a higher disorder propension, and a larger tadpole size. At the other end of the spectrum, the tadpoles are all watching you. This is conversely prompted by a higher density of ordered, smaller elements. The circles are not nucleus or bodies in cells anymore, they are the eyes of surveillance. In both cases, it's about life. Life you are watching, or life watching you.

metadata.name: Fermi Paradox #7
metadata.description:
Speculation regarding the UFO phenomenon have been going on around the world for quite sometime now. At the same time, as humanity as a collective is making some progress towards the exploration of outer space. However, the question "Are we all alone?" is still unanswered!

Fermi Paradox came from the speculative idea of the UFO phenomenon being some sort of galactic watchers sent by aliens to keep tabs on other intelligent life forms. This is a generative art project representing the watchers and the spaces being watched.

This project takes forward the idea of a digital diorama inspired by holographic dreams of our collective past, putting the viewers in place of the aliens, gazing upon different planets as the watchers go out exploring the universe.

- 16 Terrains/Landscapes
- 6 UFO Variations
- 1000 color variations
- Alien Day and Night Cycles

All generated with code via the webgl platform cables.gl.

!!Might be a bit heavy on your system!!
- Hold 'P' to check performance
- Click 'S' to save a screenshot
